com.samsung.sami.manifest.fields

Class FieldDescriptor

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.samsung.sami.manifest.fields.FieldDescriptor

  • public final class FieldDescriptor
extends Object
    A field descriptor defines a field standard name, the standard unit and the class to be used for its value.

    Valid names for FieldDescriptors follow the Java convention for variable names without the $ sign. (See: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/variables.html). We suggest using camelCase notation.

    Standard field descriptors are defined in StandardFields and standard units defined in JScience SI, NonSI classes and StandardUnits.

    If you need a field descriptor that is not standard you can define your own field descriptors.

    Sami relies on the javax.measure interfaces for units and JScience for converter. See JScience for details and JScience documentation.

    If you need a unit that is not available you can define your own units. For example: 

        // Beats per minute
   Unit BEATS = new BaseUnit<>("b");
   Unit BEATS_PER_MINUTE = BEATS.divide(MINUTE);

   // Nutritionists calories
   Unit KILO_CALORIE = SI.JOULE.times(4.184);

    Similarly, if you need a field descriptor that is not standard you can define your own field descriptors. Note that if you just want to name a field with a name different from the one in the standard field (e.g. you want a field that's called surfaceTemp, you can use the alias(String) method. (e.g. FieldDescriptor SURFACE_TEMPERATURE = TEMPERATURE.alias("surfaceTemp");).

    If you just want a field with a different value class, you can use the alias(Class) method.

    Each field descriptor must define its value class if it is not describing a field that is a structure. Supported value classes are: Boolean, Double, Float, Integer, Long and String.

    Since:
    1.1
    See Also:
    StandardFields, StandardUnits, Unit, SI, NonSI
